replies.commentText: Yes, one of the defining features of the rodent family (which include porcupines, rats, beavers, hamsters, squirrels, mice, gerbils, guinea pigs, and capybaras) are a set of incisors that never stop growing.  These constantly growing teeth mean that rodents need to constantly chew on anything and everything in order to wear down their distinctive front teeth to a manageable length.  Without this constant chewing, their teeth would eventually grow right out of their jaws and wrap around their skulls.

replies.commentText: right

I worked with  exotics for over 10 years. Contrary to popular belief, porcupines cannot "shoot" their quils. When they feel threatened, by a fox, dog, bear, etc, they puff up to look bigger and then turn their back to the preditor...when they then try to bite, they get a mouth, face, and paws full of quils! If the quils are not removed, they get deeper and can migrate through the entire body, often killing the preditor! They, otherwise are very docile and calm. They are also very smart! And as one commenter said below, they are like a giant happy hamster!!! I love porcupines!!! They are very cute, and sweet!
Thanks Victoria, I didn't know this. :)

+Alex Moores If they are relaxed, the quills lie flat with the hair.  If you pet him from head to toe, go with the lie of the guard fur, the quills lie flat.  If he's annoyed, he'll tighten the muscles around the base of the quills and then they stand up, outside of the fur.  The biggest danger is their tail.  They will back up to what they are feeling threatened by and swing the tail, trying to hit with it.  That's when you get quilled.

+Tyler RakesÂ Oh. I would still be scared if I had a porcupine for a pet, though. LOL.

+William BrennanÂ They only have spines on the back. The rest of their hair is fine. They have spines on the backside where the rest of their hair is short.
